# Clean Energy Prototype — Cursor Rules

## Working style

- Apply one small, testable task at a time; split large features.
- Do not change files outside the requested scope.
- Inspect related files before writing code.
- Summarize changed files and how to test after each task.
- When unclear, pick the simplest solution that matches existing architecture and naming.

## Language and standards

- C# compatible with Unity LTS.
- English names for classes, methods, and public members.
- Keep comments short and only where needed.
- Prefer XML docs on public APIs.
- Guard nullable risks; avoid magic numbers — use settings or named constants.

## Design

- Single Responsibility; no God Managers.
- Keep MonoBehaviours thin; put pure logic in plain C# classes.
- Use ScriptableObjects for data definitions.
- Prefer explicit interfaces/services over tight coupling.
- Minimize global singletons; do not add unnecessary patterns.

## Module folders

Place code under: Core, Camera, Map, Grid, Terrain, Resources, Buildings, Placement, Energy, Economy, Research, Settlements, Simulation, SaveLoad, UI, Debug.

## Data-driven design

Do not hardcode building costs, production, efficiency, maintenance, tech requirements, placement limits, or scenario goals — load from ScriptableObjects / config.

## Unity

- Avoid repeated `FindObjectOfType` / `GameObject.Find`.
- No allocations in `Update()`; no heavy sim every frame.
- Prefer `[SerializeField] private`; null-check prefab/scene refs.
- Log runtime errors clearly with system name and id.
- Editor tools live under `Editor` folders.

## Map and grid

- Separate visual terrain from logical grid data.
- Same seed + settings must produce the same result.
- Independent classes per generation stage.
- World↔grid conversion only through one service.
- Access cells via the service, not raw collections.

## Placement

- One rule per `PlacementRule`; return all failure reasons.
- Preview and place share the same validator.
- Deduct money only after successful placement; support rollback.

## Energy

- Separate producer / consumer / storage via interfaces.
- Rebuild network graph only when connections change.
- Deterministic energy math; no negative energy/capacity.
- Report shortage and surplus as distinct values.

## UI

- UI must not mutate game state directly — call services/commands.
- Keep debug UI separate from player UI.

## Errors

- Do not fail silently.
- Expected user errors → result models, not exceptions.
- Unexpected errors → clear exception or log, e.g. `[Placement] Building 'x' could not be placed at (12, 8): slope exceeds limit.`

## Tests

Add EditMode tests for pure logic (seed determinism, grid conversion, slope, placement, energy, storage, tech locks).

After each task report: changed files, new behavior, test steps, known limits.

## Forbidden

- Do not implement the whole game in one pass.
- No stub/`NotImplementedException` implementations.
- Do not rewrite working systems without need.
- Do not add third-party packages or change render pipeline without user approval.
- Do not restructure folders at the root without approval.

## Sprint priority

Terrain foundation first (project structure, camera, grid, seeded height map, terrain, slope, debug layers). Do not start energy, placement, or economy until terrain infrastructure is validated.
